ificance as a historical source. This volume presents the results of new, multi-disciplinary, assessment of the textand its context. What emerges from the studies collected here is a context of greater plausibility for the First Life of St Samson of Dol as an early and essentially historical text, potentially at the centre of early British Christianity and its influence on the Continent. The landscape of that Christianity is gradually emerging from the shadows and it is a landscape in which the career of St Samson, the first Insular peregrinus, is shown to be of considerable importance. LYNETTE OLSON is an Honorary Associate of the Department of History, University of Sydney. Contributors: Caroline Brett, Karen Jankulak, Constant J. Mews, Lynette Olson, Joseph-Claude Poulin, Richard Sowerby, Ian N. Wood, Jonathan M. Wooding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCeltic ChurchxHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 0aChristian saints, Celtic. 0aSamson. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBritain.  aBritish Isles.  aBrittany.  aChristianity.  aFrankish history.  aSt Samson of Dol.  aUnited Kingdom.  aWales.  aessays.  ahistory.  areligion.  atext.1 aBrett, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJankulak, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMews, Constant J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlson, Lynette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlson, Lynette, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPoulin, Joseph-Claude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSowerby, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWood,